✨ Mahu Wahine ✨ For my workroom entrance I wanted to embody everything that is Sasha Colby. I was inspired by powerful warriors going into battle.  Which is exactly what drag race is, a battle!For Hawaiians and other Polynesian cultures tattooing holds such special significance. It’s to mark a major transition is one’s life, be it grief, birth, shedding of one’s trauma, but most significant with me, tattooing is the remembering of who we are.  We Hawaiians have been dis-membered and dis-mantled for generations.  Having our voice taken from us, our land monetized, our people displaced.  But our culture and our Mana (strength) has never been erased.  These tattoos, though modern in some aspects, are a symbol of the life I have lead up to this point which has given me wisdom and connection to my ancestors that can never be erased. 🤙🏾KANAKA MAOLI 🤙🏾I am a proud descendant of countless powerful Native Hawaiian persons (Kanaka Maoli) I am a proud descendent of countless queer indigenous people. I am the product of the land I come from, the elements that make up all life forms on this planet. But most of all I am the embodiment of what it means to fully be alive in one’s body.  Growing up as a Jehovah’s Witness I realized early that religion is a subtle yet extremely effective form of colonialism. Religion has a tendency to wipe out indigenous culture and replace it with ideals to keep indigenous cultures in a position of being manipulated. The one thing that allowed me to see the glitch in the religious matrix was my queerness.  Being queer and a native Hawaiian is so deeply connected in history. Understanding this helps me understand how necessary it is for me to use this platform to amplify all things queer, native Hawaiian, while being able to showcase what I love to do more than anything else on this planet. My father is 100% Native Hawaiian, my mother is Hawaiian, Irish, and other Caucasian. My mom always wanted us children to learn about all the ethnicities that make us up.  This song Zombie has so many significances for me. Knowing why Dolores O’Riordan of The Cranberries wrote this song as a protest after a brutal IRA attack which two children, Johnathan Ball and Tim Parry were killed in the 1993 Warrington bombings, this song was written.  I was so sadden and fearful watching this in the news as a child.  This song goes a bit deeper for me because I as a child grew up in a volatile household.  My mother suffers from Bi-Polar disorder but has refused to be treated for it her entire life.  So myself and my 6 siblings were raised by a very abusive mother who wasn’t only physically abusive but mentally manipulative. I grew up very scared and very lonely, only finding solace in music and make believe.  When my mom would be on one of her episodes I remember locking myself in my room with Zombie on my walk-man trying to drown out the screams in my home with wails of sorrow by The Crabberries.  I chose to do this song for my talent because it perfectly incapsulates my inner child work. The black and white symbolizes my mother and father and the straight jacket symbolizes mental illness that not only plagues my moms psyche but the toll it took on my father which ultimately lead to my fathers suicide in 2016, he was just a few years shy of 80 years old.  The one thing that always got me through all of this was once again my queerness. I was able to accept my parents for who they really are not what I needed them to be. Although it felt like a war zone for so long growing up and I never felt that there could be a way out. I look back and am so grateful I never gave up on myself. 🤍🖤TALENT🖤🤍 For my talent showcase performance I knew I wanted to dance. Dance is the foundation to all my performances. However, I knew I didn’t want to do just any dance number. I want to show my love and connection for dance.  I remember my dance director @marcelopacleb at @247danceforce in Hawaii would always pull me out of big choreography sections to freestyle or do “my thing”. I always thought it was because I was messing up choreo and I would get hard on myself. I didn’t think I was a good enough dancer. But he told me the reason he does that to me is because while I’m a great dancer I’m actually an actor. That’s my magic. I never forgot that. That’s what I wanted to show with this talent and I’m pretty proud I must say. What does pride mean to you?

Pride means we must set aside a day or a week or a month to be proud because the rest of the world wants to make us live in shame. Pride means that we are still doing the work on making sure everyone is being treated equally and with respect and humanity. The ideal situation is that there wouldn’t have to be Pride month because we are all equal, but until then we are going to celebrate and do what the community always does; let everyone know that we’re here, we’re not going anywhere, and we have really great music and liquor.
